column9: Share one interesting fact about microplastics

Microbeads are tiny pieces of polyethylene plastic too small to be caught from water treatment plants and end up in the ocean. column8: Usually when people think of pollution, the first things to pop into mind are cups, straws, cans and larger macroscopic objects we interact with everyday. Similar to how the cup is the center of the image, people tend to only focus on these larger plastics. But by looking closer at the surrounding area, you can see that there are traces of microplastic everywhere else, all of which are rarely thought about unless brought up.

This photo is of a Rainbow Runner in the North Pacific Gyre, which is considered the largest ecosystem on Earth.  It is comprised of 20,000,000 square kilometers of ocean.  Within this vast part of the ocean, we have a swirling ball of trash and plastic that sea creatures are ingesting daily.  That photo is not even recent (circa 2008).  I can only imagine how much worse it has gotten with a growing population on Earth.  The facts are that this has been an issue for a very long time, and there's evidence of this from at least 11 years ago.
